# WHAT IT IS
#   OPC UA's `Secure Channel` layer establishes a typed mutual-
#   TLS-style encrypted channel between client and server using
#   X.509 certificates.  Each endpoint advertises a list of
#   supported `SecurityPolicy` URIs (the IEC 62541-6 standard
#   cipher suites — `Basic128Rsa15`, `Basic256`, `Basic256Sha256`,
#   `Aes128Sha256RsaOaep`, `Aes256Sha256RsaPss`, plus `None` for
#   unsecured testing) and `MessageSecurityMode` values
#   (`None`, `Sign`, `SignAndEncrypt`).  To run a non-`None`
#   security policy, both endpoints need an X.509 application
#   certificate, the certificate-store directory layout
#   (`./pki/{own,issuers,trusted,rejected,crl}` with the
#   standard PKI folder layout), and (optionally) a Certificate
#   Authority that signs each endpoint's certs.
#
#   `node-opcua-pki` is the canonical CLI tool that generates
#   all of this — and it works equally well for:
#
#     • Node-OPCUA-based OPC UA servers and clients (the
#       primary user)
#     • Any other OPC UA implementation that follows the IEC
#       62541-6 PKI layout (open62541, Eclipse Milo, FreeOpcUa
#       python-opcua-asyncio, gopcua/opcua, locka99/opcua /
#       async-opcua, Siemens / Beckhoff / Schneider PLC OPC UA
#       Servers)
#
#     The generated certs work cross-platform: a cert issued by
#     `node-opcua-pki createCA` can be used to sign certificates
#     consumed by a Siemens S7-1500 PLC, an Eclipse Milo Java
#     server, a Beckhoff TwinCAT 3 OPC UA Server, an Inductive
#     Automation Ignition gateway, or any other IEC-62541-6-
#     compliant OPC UA endpoint.
#
#   Backend: shells out to `openssl` for certificate generation
#   (verified at startup via `ensure_openssl_installed()`) plus
#   uses node-opcua-crypto's typed `generatePrivateKeyFile`,
#   `Subject`, `CertificatePurpose` helpers for the
#   in-process PKI-folder manipulation.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from lib/ca/crypto_create_CA.ts
#                       `main(argumentsList)` dispatcher +
#                       `getOptions([...])` /  `optionsDef`
#                       command-line-args option arrays;
#                       extracted via raw.githubusercontent.com
#                       fetch of lib/ca/crypto_create_CA.ts)
#
#   node-opcua-pki <COMMAND> [OPTIONS]
#   pki            <COMMAND> [OPTIONS]
#
#   Commands  (printed by `node-opcua-pki help`):
#     help                           Print top-level usage
#     version                        Print version
#     demo                           Create default certificates
#                                    for node-opcua demos
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --silent                   Silent mode
#         --dev                      Also create the
#                                    fancy/edge-case dev-test
#                                    certificates
#         --clean                    Purge existing PKI directory
#                                    (use with care!)
#     createCA                       Create a Certificate Authority
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --CAFolder <DIR>           Override CA folder location
#                                    inside PKI root
#         --keySize <BITS>           RSA key size
#                                    [values: 1024, 2048, 3072,
#                                     4096]
#         --silent                   Silent mode
#         --subject <DN>             CA certificate subject
#                                    (e.g. `/C=FR/ST=Centre/
#                                           L=Orleans/O=Sterfive/
#                                           CN=NodeOPCUA-CA`)
#     createPKI                      Create a Public Key
#                                    Infrastructure folder layout
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --PKIFolder <DIR>          Override PKI folder location
#         --keySize <BITS>           RSA key size
#         --silent                   Silent mode
#     certificate                    Create a new application
#                                    certificate (CA-signed or
#                                    self-signed)
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --CAFolder <DIR>           CA folder location
#         --PKIFolder <DIR>          PKI folder location
#         --privateKey <PATH>        Override the private-key
#                                    file
#         --silent                   Silent mode
#         -a, --applicationUri <URI> Application URI
#                                    [default: urn:{hostname}:
#                                              Node-OPCUA-Server]
#         -o, --output <PATH>        Output certificate path
#                                    [default: my_certificate.pem]
#         -s, --selfSigned           Issue a self-signed cert
#                                    (skip the CA)
#         -v, --validity <DAYS>      Certificate validity in days
#         --dns <LIST>               Comma-separated DNS SANs
#                                    [default: {hostname}]
#         --ip <LIST>                Comma-separated IP SANs
#         --subject <DN>             Certificate subject
#                                    (e.g. `/C=FR/ST=Centre/
#                                           L=Orleans/O=Sterfive/
#                                           CN=Hello`)
#     revoke <CERTIFICATE_FILE>      Revoke an existing
#                                    certificate
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --CAFolder <DIR>           CA folder location
#     csr                            Create a certificate signing
#                                    request
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --PKIFolder <DIR>          PKI folder location
#         --privateKey <PATH>        Private-key file
#         --silent                   Silent mode
#         -a, --applicationUri <URI> Application URI
#         -o, --output <PATH>        Output CSR path
#                                    [default:
#                                     my_certificate_signing_request.csr]
#         --dns <LIST>               DNS SANs
#         --ip <LIST>                IP SANs
#         --subject <DN>             Certificate subject
#     sign <CSR_FILE>                Validate a certificate
#                                    signing request and generate
#                                    a certificate
#         --root <DIR>               PKI root directory
#         --CAFolder <DIR>           CA folder location
#         --output <PATH>            Output certificate path
#     dump <CERTIFICATE_FILE>        Display a certificate
#                                    (subject, issuer, SANs,
#                                    validity, fingerprint)
#     toder <PEM_CERTIFICATE>        Convert a PEM-encoded
#                                    certificate to DER format
#                                    + print fingerprint
#     fingerprint <CERTIFICATE_FILE> Print the certificate
#                                    fingerprint (SHA-256 by
#                                    default)
#
